      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What are the top gold ETFs for 2025?</summary>
        <p>The top gold ETFs generally include SPDR Gold Shares (GLD), iShares Gold Trust (IAU), and SPDR Gold MiniShares (GLDM), which offer varying balances of high liquidity and low expense ratios.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why invest in gold ETFs instead of physical gold?</summary>
        <p>Gold ETFs provide the price exposure of physical gold but with significantly higher liquidity, lower transaction costs, and no need to secure physical storage or insurance.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Are top gold ETFs a good inflation hedge?</summary>
        <p>Historically, gold has been utilized as a store of value and a hedge against inflation and currency debasement, making gold ETFs a common component of diversified portfolios during inflationary periods.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the difference between GLD and GLDM?</summary>
        <p>While both track the price of physical gold, GLD is larger and more liquid (preferred by institutional traders), whereas GLDM has a lower expense ratio and a lower share price (often preferred by buy-and-hold retail investors).</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Do top gold ETFs pay dividends?</summary>
        <p>No. Physical gold ETFs do not generate income or pay dividends. Any returns are strictly from the capital appreciation of the underlying gold price.</p>
      </details>
